{"parse":{"title":"but","pageid":2215,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"but\"}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{clip|mul|en:'''Bu'''ngain}} with {{m|mul|t}} as a placeholder.\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n{{wp|BUT}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|but}}, {{m|enm|buten}}, {{m|enm|boute}}, {{m|enm|bouten}}, from {{inh|en|ang|būtan|t=without, outside of, except, only}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*biūtan}}, {{m|gmw-pro|*biūtini}}, equivalent to {{af|en|be-|out|nocat=1}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|but}}, {{m|sco|bot|t=outside, without, but}}, {{cog|stq|buute|t=without}}, {{cog|fy|bûten|t=outside of, apart from, other than, except, but}}, {{cog|nl|buiten|t=outside}}, {{cog|nds-nl|buten|t=outside}}, {{cog|nds-de|buuten}}, {{m|nds-de|buute|t=outside}}, obsolete {{cog|de|baußen|t=outside}}, {{cog|lb|baussen}}. Compare {{l|en|bin}}, {{l|en|about}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈbʌt/|[bʌ̈t]|a=stressed}}, {{enPR|bŭt}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-but.wav|a=Southern England}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Naomi Persephone Amethyst (NaomiAmethyst)-but.wav|a=GA}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-but.ogg|a=US}}\n*** {{IPA|en|/ˈbʊt/|a=Northern England,Irish,non-foot-strut split}}\n*** {{IPA|cy|/ˈbət/|a=South Wales,[[w:strut-comma merger|strut-comma merger]]}}\n*** {{IPA|en|/ˈbɜt/|a=[[w:fronting|/ʌ/-fronting]],Midland US,Southern US,AAVE}}\n*** {{IPA|en|/ˈbɐ̞t/|a=AU,NZ}}\n**** {{audio|en|EN-AU ck1 but.ogg|a=AU}}\n* {{IPA|en|/bət/|a=unstressed}}, {{enPR|bət}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-but2.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ʌt|s=1}}\n* {{hyph|en|but}}\n* {{homophones|en|butt}}\n\n===Preposition===\n{{en-head|prep}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|apart from}} [[apart from|Apart from]], [[except]] (for), [[excluding]].\n#: {{syn|en|barring|except for|save for|Thesaurus:except}}\n#: {{ux|en|Everyone '''but''' Father left early.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I like everything '''but''' that.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Nobody answered the door when I knocked, so I had no choice '''but''' to leave.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2011-10-23|author=Becky Ashton|work=BBC Sport\n|title=[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/15325522.stm QPR 1-0 Chelsea]\n|passage=Luiz struggled with the movement of Helguson in the box, as he collected a long ball and the Spaniard barged him over, leaving referee Chris Foy little option '''but''' to point to the spot.}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete|outside|Scotland}} [[outside|Outside]] of.\n#: {{ux|en|Away '''but''' the hoose and tell me whae's there.}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{en-adv|-}}\n\n# {{lb|en|chiefly|_|literary|or|poetic}} [[merely|Merely]], [[only]], [[just]], [[no]] [[more]] [[than]]\n#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:merely}}\n#: {{ux|en|Christmas comes  '''but''' once a year, so we can '''but''' wait till then.}}\n#* {{RQ:KJV|2 Kings|7|4|passage=If they kill us, we shall '''but''' die.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1791|author=w:Robert Burns|title=w:Ae Fond Kiss\n|passage=For to see her was to love her,<br>Love '''but''' her, and love for ever.}}\n#* {{RQ:Thoreau Walden|chapter=Economy|passage=In those days, when my hands were much employed, I read '''but''' little, but the least scraps of paper which lay on the ground, my holder, or tablecloth, afforded me as much entertainment, in fact answered the same purpose as the Iliad.}}\n#* {{RQ:Baum Wizard of Oz|passage=Now the Wicked Witch of the West had '''but''' one eye, yet that was as powerful as a telescope, and could see everywhere.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1975|author=w:Monty Python|title=w:Monty Python and the Holy Grail\n|passage=Black Knight: \"'Tis '''but''' a scratch.\" King Arthur: \"A scratch? Your arm's off!\"}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1977|author=w:Alistair Horne|title=A Savage War of Peace|location=New York|publisher=Review Books|year_published=2006|page=49\n|passage=The stony outcrops are often covered '''but''' thinly with arable soil; winters are bitingly cold, and rainfall scanty and unpredictable.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1990|author=Claude de Bèze|title=[https://books.google.co.th/books/about/1688_revolution_in_Siam.html 1688 revolution in Siam: the memoir of Father de Bèze, s.j]|translator=E. W. Hutchinson|publisher=University Press|page=153\n|passage=May the Protector of the Buddhist Faith grant me '''but''' seven more days grace of life to be quit of this disloyal couple, father and son.}}\n# {{lb|en|Australian|Geordie|Scotland|conjunctive}} [[though|Though]], [[however]].\n#: {{syn|en|even so|nevertheless|notwithstanding|yet|Thesaurus:nevertheless}}\n#: {{ux|en|I'll have to go home early '''but'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1906|author=\"Steele Rudd\"|title=Back At Our Selection|page=161|passage=\"Supposin' the chap ain't dead, '''but'''?\" Regan persisted.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1982|author={{w|Paul Radley}}|title=My Blue-Checker Corker and Me|publisher=Fontana/Collins|location=Sydney|page=16|text=‘I didn’t like that sheila that tried to latch onto him, '''but'''.’}}\n# {{ng|Used to [[repeat]] an [[adverb]] for [[emphasis]]}}; [[simply]]; [[just]]; [[absolutely]].\n#: {{ux|en|I would never, '''but''' never do such a thing!}}\n#* {{RQ:Nabokov Pnin|chapter=6.11|page=166|passage=“I would never,” said Joan, as she backed the car and worked on the wheel, “'''but''' never have allowed my child to go abroad with that old Lesbian.”}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Michelle Pauli|title=Who will win the Nobel prize for literature?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2009/oct/07/nobel-prize-literature|journal=The Guardian|date=7 Oct 2009|passage=The Nobel prize for literature is announced tomorrow lunchtime so it's time for the usual annual guessing game here on the Books desk, safe in the knowledge that we always, '''but''' always, get it wrong.}}\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{en-head|conj}}\n\n# {{l|en|however|However}}, {{l|en|although}}, {{l|en|nevertheless}}, {{l|en|on the other hand}} {{q|introducing a clause contrary to prior belief or in contrast with the preceding clause or sentence}}.\n#: {{ux|en|She is very old '''but''' still attractive.}}\n#: {{ux|en|She’s welcomed them '''but''' been rude to us.}}\n#: {{ux|en|You told me I could do that, '''but''' she said that I could not.}}\n# {{l|en|on the contrary|On the contrary}}, {{l|en|rather}} {{q|as a regular {{l|en|adversative}} conjunction, introducing a word or clause in {{l|en|contrast}} or {{l|en|contradiction}} with the preceding negative clause or sentence}}.\n#: {{ux|en|I am not rich '''but''' [I am] poor.&emsp; Not John '''but''' Peter went there.}}\n#: {{ux|en|It’s [[not so much]] that we don’t wanna go, '''but''' I just haven’t time.}}\n# {{lb|en|colloquial}} {{ng|Used at the beginning of a sentence to express [[opposition]] to a [[remark]].}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''But''' I never said you could do that!}}\n#* {{RQ:Fielding Tom Jones|volume=IV|book=X|passage=In reality, I apprehend every amorous widow on the stage would run the hazard of being condemned as a servile imitation of Dido, '''but''' that happily very few of our play-house critics understand enough of Latin to read Virgil.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-07-19|author=[http://www.theguardian.com/profile/iansample Ian Sample]|volume=189|issue=6|page=34|magazine=w:The Guardian Weekly|title=[http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2013/jul/08/irregular-bedtimes-affect-childrens-brains Irregular bedtimes may affect children's brains]|passage=Irregular bedtimes may disrupt healthy brain development in young children, according to a study of intelligence and sleeping habits.<br>Going to bed at a different time each night affected girls more than boys, '''but''' both fared worse on mental tasks than children who had a set bedtime, researchers found.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-29|volume=407|issue=8842|page=55| magazine=w:The Economist| title=[http://www.economist.com/news/international/21580191-edward-snowdens-odyssey-leaves-america-nonplussed-and-its-allies-dismayed-russia-china Travels and travails]| passage=Even without hovering drones, a lurking assassin, a thumping score and a denouement, the real-life story of Edward Snowden, a rogue spy on the run, could be straight out of the cinema. '''But''', as with Hollywood, the subplots and exotic locations may distract from the real message: America’s discomfort and its foes’ glee.}}\n# [[except|Except]] that (introducing a subordinate clause which qualifies a negative statement); also, {{q|archaic}} with omission of the subject of the subordinate clause, acting as a negative relative, \"except one that\", \"except such that\".\n#: {{ux|en|I cannot '''but''' feel offended.}}\n#: {{ux|en|My kid does nothing '''but''' watch TV all day.}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 5|IV|iii|text=And [[w:Saint Crispin's Day|Crispin Crispian]] shall ne’er go by,<br>From this day to the ending of the world,<br>'''''But''' we in it shall be rememberèd—}}\n#* {{RQ:Montaigne Florio Essayes|chapter=15|book=II|passage=There is no reason '''but''' hath another contrary unto it, saith the wisest party of Philosophers.}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Othello|III|iv|passage=And '''but''' my noble Moor is true of mind<br>{{...}} it were enough to put him to ill thinking.}}\n#* {{RQ:Keats Lamia|poem=Lamia|part=II|page=43|passage=A deadly silence step by step increased, <br> Until it seem'd a horrid presence there, <br> And not a man '''but''' felt the terror in his hair.}}\n#* {{RQ:Thoreau Walden|chapter=Economy|passage=In those days, when my hands were much employed, I read but little, '''but''' the least scraps of paper which lay on the ground, my holder, or tablecloth, afforded me as much entertainment, in fact answered the same purpose as the Iliad.}}\n# {{lb|en|colloquial}} {{n-g|Used to link an interjection to the following remark as an intensifier.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Wow! '''But''' that's amazing!}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|author={{w|Chuck Berry}}|title={{w|Johnny B. Goode}}|date=31 March 1958|artist=Chuck Berry|passage=Oh, the engineers would see him sitting in the shade / Strumming with the rhythm that the drivers made / People passing by, they would stop and say / \"Oh, my, '''but''' that little country boy could play\"}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|lyricist={{w|Elton John}}|composer={{w|Bernie Taupin}}|title={{w|Bennie and the Jets}}|album={{w|Goodbye Yellow Brick Road}}|artist=Elton John, {{w|Davey Johnstone}}, {{w|Dee Murray}}, {{w|Nigel Olsson}}|date=4 February 1974|note=track 3|text=Say, Candy and Ronnie, have you seen them yet? / Ooh, '''but''' they're so spaced out / B-B-B-Bennie and the Jets / Oh, '''but''' they're weird and they're wonderful / Oh, Bennie, she's really keen}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2013|author=Nora Roberts|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=BiX8HdYyPY0C&pg=PT25|title=Irish Thoroughbred|page=25|publisher=Little, Brown|isbn=9781405523516\n|passage=\"Jakers, '''but''' we worked.\" With a long breath she shut her eyes. \"But it was too much for one woman and a half-grown girl {{...}}\"}}\n# {{lb|en|archaic}} Without it also being the case that; unless that (introducing a necessary concomitant).\n#: {{ux|en|[[it never rains but it pours|It never rains '''but''' it pours]]}}\n#: {{ux|en|I never hear this song '''but''' I think of you.}}\n#* {{RQ:Spenser Faerie Queene|II|VI|passage=No arboret with painted blossomes drest, / And smelling sweet, '''but''' there it might be found {{...}}}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Hamlet|II|ii|passage=For there is nothing either good or bad, '''but''' thinking makes it so}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Except with; unless with; without.\n#* {{RQ:Fuller Holy Warre|chapter=Unseasonable Discords betwixt King Baldwine and His Mother; Her Strength in Yeelding to Her Sonne|page=84|passage=This man unable to manage his own happineſſe, grew ſo inſolent that he could not go, '''but''' either ſpurning his equals, or trampling on his inferiours.}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Only; solely; merely.\n#* {{RQ:Milton Of Reformation|passage=Observe '''but''' how their own principles combat one another.}}\n#* {{RQ:Dryden Metamorphoses|passage=a formidable man '''but''' to his friends}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[until|Until]].\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Macbeth|passage='Tshall not be long '''but''' I'll be here again.}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete|following a negated expression of improbability}} [[that|That]]. {{defdate|16th–19th c.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1784|author=w:Joshua Reynolds|editors=w:John Ingamells; w:John Edgcumbe|title=The Letters of Sir Joshua Reynolds|publisher=Yale|year_published=2000|page=131\n|passage=It is not impossible '''but''' next year I may have the honour of waiting on your Lordship at St. Asaph, If I go to Ireland I certainly will go that way.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1789|author={{w|John Moore (Scottish physician)|John Moore}}|title=Zeluco|publisher=Valancourt|year_published=2008|page=132\n|passage=“I am convinced, if you were to press this matter earnestly upon her, she would consent.”<br>“It is not impossible '''but''' she might,” said Madame de Seidlits {{...}}.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1813|journal=Journal of Natural Philosophy|month=July\n|passage=It is not improbable '''but''' future observations will add Pliny's Well to the class of irregular reciprocators.}}\n\n====Usage notes====\nIt is generally considered colloquial to use ''but'' at the beginning of a sentence:<br>\n“'''But''' the tool has its uses!”<br>\nOther conjunctions, such as ''however'' or ''nevertheless'', are considered more proper for that end, and are thus preferred in formal writing:<br>\n“However, the tool still has its uses.”<br>\n“Nevertheless, the instrument could still be used for its ''[[raison d'être]]''.”\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|en|abbur}} {{q|Chester}}\n* {{sense|except}} {{l|en|bar}}, {{l|en|unless}}, {{l|en|excepting}}, {{l|en|excluding}}, {{l|en|with the exception of}}, {{l|en|without}}\n* {{sense|however}} {{l|en|yet}}, {{l|en|although}}, {{l|en|ac}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|although}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|maar}}\n* Aleut: {{t|ale|-iiĝali-}}, {{t|ale|-ĝdagali-}}, {{t|ale|-tagali-}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|لٰكِن}}, {{t+|ar|لٰكِنَّ}}, {{t|ar|وَلٰكِن|tr=wa-lākin}}, {{t|ar|وَلٰكِنَّ|tr=wa-lākinna}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|لكن|tr=laken}}, {{t|arz|بس|tr=bas}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{t|acw|بس|tr=bass}}, {{t|acw|لكن|tr=lākin}}\n*: South Levantine Arabic: {{t|ajp|لكن|tr=lāken}}, {{t|ajp|بسّ|tr=bass}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|թեեւ}}, {{t+|hy|բայց}}, {{t+|hy|սակայն}}\n* Assamese: {{t|as|পিচে}}, {{t|as|পাচে}}, {{t|as|কিন্তু}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|pero}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|amma}}, {{t+|az|lakin}}, {{t+|az|ancaq}}, {{t+|az|fəqət}}\n* Basque: {{t+|eu|baina}}, {{t|eu|nahiz eta}}\n* Belarusian: {{t+|be|але́}}\n* Bengali: {{t+|bn|কিন্তু}}\n* Bhojpuri: {{t|bho|लेकिन}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|met}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|но}}, {{t+|bg|оба́че}}, {{t+|bg|а́ма}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my|ဒါပေမဲ့}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|mes}}, {{t+|ca|però}}, {{t+|ca|mas}} {{qualifier|old}}, {{t|ca|emperò}}\n* Chechen: {{t|ce| тӏаккха}}, {{t|ce|амма}}, {{t|ce|-ехь}}, {{t|ce|-ам}}, {{t|ce|делахь}}, {{t|ce|-ча}}, {{t|ce|-ахь}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t|yue|但係}}, {{t|yue|不過|tr=bat1 gwo3}}\n*: Hakka: {{t|hak|但係|tr=than-he}}, {{t|hak|毋過|tr=m̀-ko}}\n*: Hokkien: {{t+|nan-hbl|但是|tr=tān-sī}}, {{t+|nan-hbl|不而過|tr=put-jî-kò, put-lî-kò}}, {{t+|nan-hbl|毋過|tr=m̄-koh, m̄-kò, m̄-kù}}, {{t|nan-hbl|無過|tr=bû-kò}}, {{t+|nan-hbl|不過|tr=put-kò}}, {{t+|nan-hbl|總是|tr=chóng-sī}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|可是}}, {{t+|cmn|但是}}, {{t+|cmn|不過}}\n* Chong: {{t|cog|tr=pəntɛː}}\n* Circassian:\n*: East Circassian: {{t+|kbd|ауэ}}\n*: West Circassian: {{t|ady|ау}}\n* Comorian:\n*: Maore Comorian: {{t|swb|ɓadi}}\n*: Mwali Comorian: {{t|wlc|walakini}}\n*: Ngazidja Comorian: {{t|zdj|sha}}, {{t|zdj|lakini}}, {{t|zdj|amma}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|ale}}\n* Dalmatian: {{t|dlm|mui}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|men}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|maar}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|sed}}\n* Estonian: {{t+|et|kuid}}, {{t+|et|aga}}, {{t+|et|a}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}\n* Faroese: {{t+|fo|men}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|mutta}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|mais}}, {{t+|fr|cependant}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|porén}}, {{t+|gl|macar}}, {{t|gl|maxer}}, {{t|gl|magar}}, {{t|gl|inanque}}, {{t|gl|inda que}}, {{t|gl|malia que}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|მაგრამ}}, {{t|ka|თუმცა}}\n* German: {{t+|de|aber}}, aber {{t+|de|trotzdem}}\n*: East Central German: {{t|gmw-ecg|abr}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|μολονότι}}, {{t+|el|παρόλο}}, {{t+|el|καίτοι}}, {{t+|el|αν και}}\n* Greenlandic: {{t|kl|-galuar}}, {{t|kl|-kaluar}}, {{t|kl|-raluar}}\n* Guarani:\n*: Mbya Guarani: {{t|gun|ha'e rã}}\n* Gujarati: {{t|gu|પણ}}\n* Hawaiian: {{t|haw|akā}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|אֲבָל|tr=avál}}, {{t+|he|אוּלָם|tr=ulám}}, {{t+|he|אַךְ|tr=akh}}, {{t+|he|בְּרַם|tr=b'rám}}\n* Hindi: {{t|hi|लेकिन}}, {{t+|hi|पर}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|de}}, {{t+|hu|viszont}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|en}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|ma}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|kecuali}}, {{t+|id|tetapi}}, {{t+|id|tapi}}\n* Inuktitut: {{t|iu|-galuaq-}}, {{t|iu|-kaluaq-}}, {{t|iu|-raluaq-}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|ach}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|ma}}, {{t+|it|però}}, {{t+|it|tuttavia}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|が|tr=ga}}, {{t+|ja|けれど|tr=keredo}}, {{t+|ja|けれども|tr=keredomo}}, {{t+|ja|けど|tr=kedo}}, {{t+|ja|しかし|tr=shikashi}}, {{t+|ja|でも|tr=demo}}\n* Kannada: {{t+|kn|ಆದರೆ}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|бірақ}}\n* Khasi: {{t|kha|hynrei}}\n* Khmer: {{t+|km|តែ}}, {{t+|km|ប៉ុន្តែ}}, {{t+|km|ក៏ប៉ុន្តែ|tr=kɑɑ pontae}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|그러나}}, {{t+|ko|하지만}}, {{t+|ko|지만|alt=-지만}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{t+|kmr|lê}}, {{t+|kmr|feqet}}, {{t+|kmr|bes}}, {{t+|kmr|lêbelê}}, {{t+|kmr|ema}}\n* Kuy: {{t|kdt|tr=paj}}\n* Lao: {{t|lo|ແຕ່}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|sed}}, {{t+|la|at}}, {{t|la|ast}}, {{t+|la|tamen}}, {{t+|la|autem}}\n* Latvian: {{t+|lv|bet}}, {{t|lv|taču}}\n* Ligurian: {{t|lij|ma}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t+|lt|bet}}, {{t+|lt|tačiau}}, {{t+|lt|nors}}\n* Louisiana Creole: {{t|lou|mé}}\n* Lü: {{t-needed|khb}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|но}}, {{t|mk|а́ма}}\n* Malay: {{t|ms|tetapi}}\n* Malayalam: {{t+|ml|പക്ഷേ}}\n* Maltese: {{t|mt|iżda}}\n* Ma